[{"id":31110,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math><mi>C</mi><msup><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>  and  <math><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math><mi>C</mi><msup><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> and <math><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math><mi>C</mi><msup><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>  and  <math><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi><msup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>  and  <math><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a0e88e60-e0d0-4340-95f4-95348b1e5f11-image.png\" style=\"width: 739px; height: 112px;\" /><br /><br />Chlorine on reaction with hot and concentrated sodium hydroxide gives&nbsp;<math><mi>C</mi><msup><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><mtext> </mtext><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-&#160;</mo></mrow></msubsup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31126,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XeO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XeOF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>During the hydrolysis the oxidation of xenon not changes in xenon hexafluoride.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>XeOF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>HF</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8201;</mo><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>XeOF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>SiF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31127,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>.</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>.</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>As we know that, the peroxodisulfuric acid and pyrosulfuric acid are the examples of oxyacid and both contain sulfur oxygen and sulfur hydrogen bond. In the oxyacids, the oxygen is the main element.</p><p>Peroxodisulphuric acid<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/klykcgbllqmrilipnybprjytaknbwgktmybanowczhkjcqnnxl.jpeg\" /><br /><br />Pyrosulphuric acid<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/shmabclesbxqngfftnjexvommaztknsbaibbgthdhciucmhjpy.jpeg\" /></p><p>The number of S=O and S&minus;OH bonds present in peroxodisulphuric acid and pyrosulphuric acid respectively are (4 and 2) and (4 and 2).&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31090,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>NO</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31057,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["White&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","&nbsp; Red <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>NaH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Red</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Alkali</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow></mrow></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math></p><p>White&nbsp;Phosphorous react with alkali metal hydroxide to form phosphine and a salt of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msubsup><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>. While red phosphorous react with alkali to give oxoacid of phosphorus with no&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>&nbsp;bonds.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31071,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cc64331f-d795-4c02-9c60-9951f372557c-image.png\" style=\"width: 296px; height: 194px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31006,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The total number of electrons that an atom either gains or loses in order to form a chemical bond with another atom is known as the Oxidation Number.</p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p> Let the oxidation number of S be x.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>(</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>+</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo> </mo><mo>+</mo><mo> </mo><mn>3</mn><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mn>0</mn><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></math> </p><p>Similarly the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo></math>oxidation state of sulphur is shown by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SOCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>and</mi><mo> </mo><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnlines=\"solid\" frame=\"solid\" rowlines=\"solid\"><mtr><mtd><mtext> Compounds </mtext></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>SOCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mtext> O.S.of Sulphur: </mtext></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31100,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math><mn>2</mn></math>","<math><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mn>4</mn></math>","<math><mn>3</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>P</mtext> <mn>4</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mtext>NaOH</mtext><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mtext>O</mtext><mo>→</mo><munder> <mrow> <mn>3</mn><msub> <mrow> <mtext>NaH</mtext></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>PO</mtext></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mfenced> <mtext>x</mtext> </mfenced></mrow> </munder> <mo>+</mo><msub> <mrow> <mtext>PH</mtext></mrow> <mn>3</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>NaH</mtext></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>PO</mtext></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo><mtext>HCl</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext>NaCl</mtext><mo>+</mo><munder> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msub> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>PO</mtext></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mrow> <mfenced> <mtext>Y</mtext></mfenced></mrow></munder></mrow></math><br /><br />&nbsp; <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/18QJ.PNG\" style=\"width: 304px; height: 130px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31144,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{XeOF}_4$","$\\mathrm{XeO}_3$","$\\mathrm{XeO}_3 \\mathrm{~F}_2$","$\\mathrm{XeOF}_2$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$$\n\\text { The shape of } \\mathrm{XeO}_3 \\mathrm{~F}_2 \\text { is Trigonal bipyramidal. }\n$$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/l5cP02qIq9GvWmO9JOUt3cdkmvEYhx8gPZSX7HPbUoo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n(Trigonal bipyramidal Structure)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30992,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["4","6","3","5"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{N}-\\mathrm{N} < \\mathrm{P}-\\mathrm{P}$ : single $(\\sigma)$ bond strength\n\nDue to L.P.-L.P. replusion\nand maximum possible covalency of nitrogen is 4 .","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31049,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ba</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ba</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></mover><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>(Thermally stable and does not undergo decomposition further)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ba</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></mover><mi>Ba</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>Ba</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></mover><mn>2</mn><mi>BaO</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31078,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><munder><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>Limited</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>water</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder><mo>&#10230;</mo><msub><mi>XeO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>HF</mi></math></p><p>Structure of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b08a4ffa-9a55-4966-9849-8df9a45b10ea-image.png\" style=\"width: 217px; height: 217px;\" /></p><p>Total l.p. on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>19</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31061,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Metallic oxides are basic in nature, Oxides of non-metals are mostly acidic in nature and some are neutral or amphoteric.</p><p>Among the given oxides&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;is a metallic oxide, and&nbsp;it is basic in nature.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a non-metal oxide and it is acidic in nature.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NO</mi></math>&nbsp;are non-metallic oxides but are neutral in nature.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>As</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is an Amphoteric oxide. It reacts with both acids and bases.</p><p>So, The number of amphoteric oxides is 1.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31119,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["9","6","12","18"],"answer":2,"solution":"$$\n\\text { The number of } \\mathrm{P}-\\mathrm{O} \\text { bonds in } \\mathrm{P}_4 \\mathrm{O}_6=12\n$$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cseWn-0AlJg5ZOGAXdIdMCaXrPqhTaQJrP8EIS90gs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":31080,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NO</mi><mtext>&#160;and&#160;</mtext><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mtext>&#160;and&#160;</mtext><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mtext>&#160;and&#160;</mtext><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NO</mi><mtext>&#160;and&#160;</mtext><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NO</mi></math> are neutral oxides of nitrogen <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;are acidic oxides.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31159,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Electron affinity","Bond dissociation energy","Hydration enthalpy","Ionization enthalpy"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":31097,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Phosphinic acid is hypo phosphorous acid&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>NaH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>For neutrization</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi>acid</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi>base</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mi>mL</mi></msub></mfenced><mi>NaOH</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mi>NaOH</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30978,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["NO and $[\\text{Fe(NO)}]\\text{SO}_4$","NO$_2$ and $[\\text{Fe(NO}_2)]\\text{SO}_4$","N$_2$O and $[\\text{Fe(N}_2\\text{O})]\\text{SO}_4$","N$_2$O$_4$ and $[\\text{Fe(N}_2\\text{O}_4)]\\text{SO}_4$"],"answer":0,"solution":"The brown ring test is used for the detection of nitrate ($\\text{NO}_3^-$) or nitrite ($\\text{NO}_2^-$) ions.<br><br>In this test, nitric oxide (NO) gas is evolved which reacts with the freshly prepared ferrous sulphate ($\\text{FeSO}_4$) solution to form a brown ring of nitroso ferrous sulphate.<br><br>The gas $X$ is NO.<br><br>The reaction is given by:<br><br>$\\text{FeSO}_4 + \\text{NO} \\rightarrow [\\text{Fe(NO)}]\\text{SO}_4$<br><br>The actual composition of the brown ring complex is $[\\text{Fe(H}_2\\text{O})_5(\\text{NO})]\\text{SO}_4$, which is often represented as $[\\text{Fe(NO)}]\\text{SO}_4$.<br><br>Thus, $X$ is NO and $Y$ is $[\\text{Fe(NO)}]\\text{SO}_4$.<br><br>Answer: NO and $[\\text{Fe(NO)}]\\text{SO}_4$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31156,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{HClO}_3$ and $\\mathrm{Cl}_2 \\mathrm{O}$","$\\mathrm{HClO}_2$ and $\\mathrm{HClO}_4$","$\\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\\mathrm{Cl}_2 \\mathrm{O}$","$\\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\\mathrm{HClO}_3$"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":31139,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In case of noble gases, Vander waal forces exist between atoms which are directly proportional to size of elements.</p><p>Due to bigger size of Xe, it&#39;s electron cloud gets polarized more and as a result it has stronger Van Der Waals forces leading to a higher boiling point.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":31052,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Both assertion and reason are correct and reason is the correct explanation of assertion.","Both assertion and reason are correct and but reason is not&nbsp;the correct explanation of assertion.","Assertion is correct and reason is incorrect","Assertion is incorrect and reason is correct"],"answer":0,"solution":"Due to small size and high electronegativity F can not act as central atom in higher oxidation state.So,&nbsp;fluorine forms only one oxoacid.The other halogens form several oxoacids.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31082,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Br</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>FeI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><mfenced><mi>Unstable</mi></mfenced></munder><mo>&#10230;</mo><munder><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>FeI</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mfenced><mi>Stable</mi></mfenced></munder><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Due to strong reducing nature of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#10230;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;remaining halides of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> are stable.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30988,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["Oxidising and acidic","Reducing and basic","Reducing and acidic","Oxidising and basic"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{TeO}_2$ is oxidizing in nature because it can be reduced from +4 oxidation state to lower oxidation state.<br />$\\mathrm{TeH}_2$ due to less bond dissociation energy easily breaks and hence acidic in nature.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31011,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> is true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is false</p>","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> are true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is the correct explaination of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> is false but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is true","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> are true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is NOT the correct explaination of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When glycine is treated with chlorine in presence of red phosphorus, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HVZ</mi></math> reaction takes place i.e., substitution of chlorine takes place at alpha carbon.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c892f76-f2a1-4439-a2b6-0a9ad81f49c3.png\" style=\"width: 460px; height: 116px;\" /></p><p>A molecule with two chiral carbons is not always optically active. Suppose the following compound is having two chiral carbons but optically inactive due to internal compensation of optical rotation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d8f1bbe6-f14b-4395-8037-628f3a9c52b9.png\" style=\"width: 142px; height: 178px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31008,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Br</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Br</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Br</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Fluorine oxidises water to oxygen whereas chlorine &amp; bromine react with water to form corresponding <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HX</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>HOX</mi></math> acids.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow/></mover><mn>4</mn><mi>HF</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow/></mover><mi>HCl</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>HOCl</mi></math></p><p>The reaction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;with water is nonspontaneous. In fact <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> can be oxidised by oxygen in acidic medium. It is why the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> in nature is not present in that much amount as other halides are present in nature.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31077,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["acidic","basic","amphoteric","neutral"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d6ce45b1-126a-4fa4-8fc4-7c38c98ad2a3-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 80px;\" /></p><p>Ans. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math> is acidic in nature.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30984,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["1312","1402","1086","801"],"answer":1,"solution":"The p-block element E forms a binary cation $(EH_x)^+$ with hydrogen and produces a basic mercury(II) amido-iodide precipitate with $K_2HgI_4$ in alkaline medium.<br>This behavior is characteristic of ammonia (NH₃), which forms the ammonium ion $(NH_4)^+$ and reacts with Nessler's reagent ($K_2HgI_4$) to form a characteristic brown/yellow precipitate.<br>Therefore, E is Nitrogen (N), a Group 15 p-block element with electronic configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^3$.<br>Nitrogen has a notably high first ionization enthalpy compared to other group 15 elements due to:<br>Small atomic radius<br>High effective nuclear charge<br>Stable half-filled p³ subshell configuration<br>The first ionization enthalpy of nitrogen is 1402 kJ/mol.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31088,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> is inert towards hydrolysis<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> answere is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31031,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Xe</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Ne</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>He</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>He</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Ne</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Xe</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>He</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Ne</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>He</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Ne</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>All the given elements belong&nbsp;to the group - 18. All noble gases have general electronic configuration&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>ns</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>np</mi><mn>6</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;except helium which has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>. Since noble gases have stable electronic configuration, they have&nbsp;no tendency to accept the electron and therefore, have large positive values of electron gain enthalpy.</p><p>Values of electron gain enthalpy of all the elements are given in the below table</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 300px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Element</td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>egH</mi><mo>[</mo><mi>KJ</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>]</mo></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>He</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>48</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ne</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>116</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Kr</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>96</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Xe</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>77</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>So, the order is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>He</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Ne</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31024,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 15, 16, 17 & 18)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Hypophosphoric acid&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f9eccd32-8ca2-4038-9e71-3f715fc3d3a2-9896189.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 220px;\" /></p><p>The oxidation state of phosphorus is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]